{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: New partial result.","id":"vf_2f5ccbaaf46f1e7a","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos868.erdos_868.variants.Hartter_Nathanson https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos868.erdos_868.variants.Hartter_Nathanson.","id":"vf_6353e169f75c21ee","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #868: declared status 'solved'. Formalized: yes. If $A$ is an additive basis of order $2$, and $1_A\\ast 1_A(n)\\to \\infty$ as $n\\to \\infty$, then must $A$ contain a minimal additive basis of order $2$? (i.e. such that deleting any element creates infinitely many $n\\not\\in A+A$)\n\nWhat if $1_A\\ast 1_A(n) >\\epsilon \\log n$ (for all large $n$, for arbitrary fixed $\\epsilon>0$)? Current best: Erd\\H{o}s and Nathanson \\cite{ErNa89} proved that, for any $t$, there exists $A$ such that $1_A\\ast 1_A(n)\\geq t$ for all large $n$ and yet $A$ does not contain a minimal asymptotic basis of order $2$. Prize: no. Tags: additive basis, number theory.","id":"vf_f3c371c720a85430","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/868.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_2f5ccbaaf46f1e7a","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:868","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_6353e169f75c21ee","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:868","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between acc